A production-like function model and a budget optimization model were applied to evaluate how treatment or prevention could improve QoC-scores in hospital bed management. These models could become an easy application tool to guide decision makers in their investment decisions. The analysis does not require a large number of data and the interpretation of the results is straightforward. The models help clarify the dilemma of investing in an optimal mix of both treatment and prevention that will find the right balance between those two forces in healthcare development programs, and thus improving the QoC-scores in the hospital environment.
